            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale?</h2>
              <p>
                The Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale (SSHWS) is a 1–5 rating
                based on a tropical cyclone’s
                <strong>maximum sustained wind speed</strong>. It is used for
                storms that reach hurricane strength (at least 74 mph / 119
                km/h). Each category describes the
                <strong>typical level of wind damage</strong>
                expected if the storm’s core passes over an area with typical
                building standards.
              </p>
              <p>
                The scale does <strong>not</strong> directly include storm
                surge, rainfall flooding, or tornadoes, even though these
                hazards often cause the most loss of life.
              </p>

              <h3>Official wind speed ranges</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  By maximum sustained wind (1-minute average at 10 m height):
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc ml-5">
                  <li><strong>Category 1:</strong> 74–95 mph (119–153 km/h)</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Category 2:</strong> 96–110 mph (154–177 km/h)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Category 3:</strong> 111–129 mph (178–208 km/h)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Category 4:</strong> 130–156 mph (209–251 km/h)
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>Category 5:</strong> ≥ 157 mph (≥ 252 km/h)</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-gray-600">
                  Below 74 mph, storms are classified as tropical depressions or
                  tropical storms, not hurricanes.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How this calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool lets you enter a wind speed in
                <strong>mph, km/h, knots, or m/s</strong>. Internally, it:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Converts your input to miles per hour (mph).</li>
                <li>
                  Compares the mph value to the official SSHWS thresholds.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Returns the corresponding category and a concise damage
                  description.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Shows equivalent speeds in the other units for quick
                  reference.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Unit conversion formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Conversions used:</p>
                <ul class="list-disc ml-5">
                  <li>\(\text{mph} = \text{km/h} \div 1.609344\)</li>
                  <li>\(\text{mph} = \text{knots} \times 1.150779\)</li>
                  <li>\(\text{mph} = \text{m/s} \times 2.236936\)</li>
                  <li>\(\text{km/h} = \text{mph} \times 1.609344\)</li>
                  <li>\(\text{knots} = \text{mph} \div 1.150779\)</li>
                  <li>\(\text{m/s} = \text{mph} \div 2.236936\)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h2>Interpreting categories and real-world risk</h2>
              <p>
                The category is a <strong>wind-only</strong> rating. Actual risk
                depends on many factors:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Distance from the storm center and eyewall</li>
                <li>Local building codes and construction quality</li>
                <li>Storm size, forward speed, and angle of approach</li>
                <li>Coastal vs. inland location and elevation</li>
                <li>Storm surge and rainfall flooding potential</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For example, a slow-moving Category 1 storm with extreme
                rainfall can be more dangerous than a fast-moving Category 3
                that stays offshore.
              </p>

              <h3>Typical impacts by category</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Category 1–2:</strong> Dangerous to extremely
                  dangerous winds, scattered to widespread power outages, tree
                  damage, some roof and siding damage.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Category 3–5 (Major hurricanes):</strong> Devastating
                  to catastrophic damage, many structures damaged or destroyed,
                  long-duration outages, areas potentially uninhabitable for
                  weeks or months.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Safety tips when using the Saffir-Simpson scale</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Do not focus only on the category number; check official
                  forecasts for surge and rainfall.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Follow evacuation orders even for Category 1 or 2 storms if
                  you are in a surge-prone area.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Complete preparations before tropical-storm-force winds (≥ 39
                  mph / 63 km/h) arrive.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use multiple trusted sources: National Hurricane Center, local
                  meteorological agencies, and emergency management.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and disclaimers</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is for
                <strong>educational and planning support</strong> only. It does
                not replace official forecasts, warnings, or evacuation
                instructions. Always follow guidance from your national
                meteorological service and local emergency management
                authorities.
              </p>
            </section>

